{"id":"2009.10286","submitter":"Timothy Moroney","authors":"Riley M. Whebell, Timothy J. Moroney, Ian W. Turner, Ravindra\n  Pethiyagoda, Scott W. McCue","title":"Implicit reconstructions of thin leaf surfaces from large, noisy point\n  clouds","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Thin surfaces, such as the leaves of a plant, pose a significant challenge\nfor implicit surface reconstruction techniques, which typically assume a\nclosed, orientable surface. We show that by approximately interpolating a point\ncloud of the surface (augmented with off-surface points) and restricting the\nevaluation of the interpolant to a tight domain around the point cloud, we need\nonly require an orientable surface for the reconstruction. We use polyharmonic\nsmoothing splines to fit approximate interpolants to noisy data, and a\npartition of unity method with an octree-like strategy for choosing subdomains.\nThis method enables us to interpolate an N-point dataset in O(N) operations. We\npresent results for point clouds of capsicum and tomato plants, scanned with a\nhandheld device. An important outcome of the work is that sufficiently smooth\nleaf surfaces are generated that are amenable for droplet spreading\nsimulations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Sep 2020 02:34:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 12 Apr 2021 23:46:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-04-14"}
{"id":"2009.10287","submitter":"Yuxin Zhao","authors":"Y. X. Zhao, Cong Chen, Xian-Lei Sheng and Shengyuan A. Yang","title":"Switching spinless and spinful topological phases with projective $PT$\n  symmetry","comments":"5 pages for the main text, plus 6 pages for the supplemental\n  material, to appear in Phys. Rev. Lett","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 126, 196402 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.126.196402","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall cond-mat.other cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A fundamental dichotomous classification for all physical systems is\naccording to whether they are spinless or spinful. This is especially crucial\nfor the study of symmetry-protected topological phases, as the two classes have\ndistinct symmetry algebra. As a prominent example, the spacetime inversion\nsymmetry $PT$ satisfies $(PT)^2=\\pm 1$ for spinless/spinful systems, and each\nclass features unique topological phases. Here, we reveal a possibility to\nswitch the two fundamental classes via $\\mathbb{Z}_2$ projective\nrepresentations. For $PT$ symmetry, this occurs when $P$ inverses the gauge\ntransformation needed to recover the original $\\mathbb{Z}_2$ gauge connections\nunder $P$. As a result, we can achieve topological phases originally unique for\nspinful systems in a spinless system, and vice versa. We explicitly demonstrate\nthe claimed mechanism with several concrete models, such as Kramers degenerate\nbands and Kramers Majorana boundary modes in spinless systems, and real\ntopological phases in spinful systems. Possible experimental realization of\nthese models is discussed. Our work breaks a fundamental limitation on\ntopological phases and opens an unprecedented possibility to realize intriguing\ntopological phases in previously impossible systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Sep 2020 02:35:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 8 Apr 2021 04:43:03 GMT"}],"update